    </image>
    Algebraically, <m>C'(x) = \displaystyle\lim_{\Delta x\rightarrow 0} \dfrac{\Delta y}{\Delta x} = \dfrac{dy}{dx}</m>
  </p>
  <p>
    Our goal in this section will be to <em>find</em> or <em>take</em> the derivative of a given function.  We will use the following notation 
    <me>
      f'(x) = \dfrac{d}{dx}\Big[ \ f(x) \ \Big]
    </me>
    as a shorthand for the sentence 
    "Find the derivative of <m>f(x)</m> with respect to <m>x</m>"
  </p>
  <p>
    Some students find the <m>\ddx{\cdots}</m> notation difficult to read because of the large number of symbols involved. 
    In that case, you can use an alternate notation:
    <me>
      f'(x) = \D{ f(x) } 
    </me>
    In this notation, we use square brackets with an apostraphe on the right to say "take the derivative of the function inside the brackets. " 
  </p>
</introduction>


<section xml:id="sec_basicrules1">
  <title>Basic Derivative Rules</title>
  
  <example>
    <title>Slope of a Constant Function</title>
    
    <p>
      Some functions always output the same number <m>c</m>, regardless of the input <m>x</m>.  These functions have the form <m>f(x) = c</m>, and their graphs are horizontal lines. 
      <image xml:id="img_constantfn" width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[axes] (-1,0)--(4,0);
            \draw[axes] (0,-1)--(0,4);
            \draw[curve, dashed] (-1,3) -- (4,3) node [above right] {$f(x) = c$};
            \node[above left] at (0,3) {$c$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>
      This function is horizontal everywhere, so has a slope of <m>0</m> for all <m>x</m>.  In other words, we have 
      <me>
        f'(x) = \ddx{c} = 0 
      </me>
      which is the same as saying 
      <me>
        \D{ c } = 0
      </me>
      
    </p>
  </example>

  <exploration>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f(x) = 3</m>.  Find <m>f'(x)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <m>f'(x) = \ddx{3} = 0</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        Equivalently, we could use our bracket notation to write <m>\D{ 3 } = 0</m>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exploration>

  <example>
    <title>Slope of a Linear Function</title>

    <p>
      Some functions are lines.  These functions have the form <m>f(x) = m x + b</m> for some number <m>m,b</m>. 
      <image xml:id="img_linearfn" width="50%">
        <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}
            \draw[axes] (-1,0)--(4,0);
            \draw[axes] (0,-1)--(0,4);
            \draw[grid] (-0.5,-0.5) grid (3.5,3.5);
            \draw[curve, dashed] (-1,1) -- (4,3.5) node [above right] {$f(x) = c$};
            \node[above left] at (0,3) {$c$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
      </image>

      This function has the same slope everywhere, which is equal to the slope <m>m</m> of the line.  In other words, we have 
      <me>
        f'(x) = \ddx{ m x + b } = m  
      </me>
      which is the same as saying 
      <me>
        \D{ m x + b} = m
      </me>
    </p>    
  </example>

  <exploration>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f(x) = 3x + 2</m>.  Find <m>f'(x) </m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <m>f'(x) = \ddx{3x + 2} = 3</m>
      </p>
      <p>
        Equivalently, we could use our bracket notation to write <m>\D{ 3x + 2} = 3</m>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exploration>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>Slopes of Lines and Constant Functions</title>
    <p>
      Suppose that <m>c,m,b</m> are constant numbers.  We have the following derivative shortcuts
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>  
        <m>\ddx{c} = 0</m>
      </li>
      <li>
          <m>\ddx{m\cdot x + b} = m</m>
      </li>
      <li>
          <m>\ddx{x} = 1</m>
      </li>
    </ul>
    In bracket notation, this is
    <ul>
      <li>  
        <m>\D{c} = 0</m>
      </li>
      <li>
          <m>\D{m\cdot x + b} = m</m>
      </li>
      <li>
          <m>\D{x} = 1</m>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </paragraphs>

  <p>
    More complex functions need derivative <em>templates</em> or <em>shortcut rules</em>.  
    For example, the function <m>f(x) = x^2</m> has <em>different slopes</em> at different values of <m>x</m>.
          <interactive platform="jsxgraph" width="30%" preview="jsxgraph-findingslopefromtangent-exercise2b.png">
