    Is there a nice <em>formula</em> that gives us the slope as a function of <m>x</m>?  Surprisingly, the answer is <em>also</em> yes.
  </p>

  <paragraphs>
    <title>The Derivative of <m>\ln(x)</m></title>
    <me>
      \ddx{\ln(x) } = \dfrac{1}{x}
    </me>
    In bracket notation, this is 
    <me>
      [ \ln(x) ]' = \dfrac{1}{x}
    </me>
  </paragraphs>

  <exploration>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f(x) = 3\ln(x) - x^{1/3}</m>.  
        Find <m>f'(x)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <md>
          <mrow> f'(x) = \amp  \ddx{ 3\ln(x) - x^{1/3} } </mrow>
          <mrow>= \amp \ddx{3\ln(x)} - \ddx{x^{1/3}}</mrow>
          <mrow>= \amp 3\ddx{\ln(x)} - \frac{1}{3} \cdot x^{\frac{1}{3}-1} </mrow>
          <mrow>= \amp 3\cdot \dfrac{1}{x} - \frac{1}{3} \cdot x^{-2/3} </mrow>        
        </md>
      </p>
    </solution>
  </exploration>

  <assemblage xml:id="assemblage-deriv-explog">
    <title>Derivatives of Exponentials and Logarithms</title>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ddx{e^x} = e^x </m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\ddx{\ln(x)} = \frac{1}{x}</m>
          </p>
        </li>
