  <exploration xml:id="ex_derivatives_explog">
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x) = 12e^x - 2</m>.  Find <m>f'(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>[12e^x - 2]'  \amp = [12e^x]' - [2]'</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = 12 [e^x]' - 0</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp 12 e^x</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x) = 7\ln(x) + 5</m>.  Find <m>f'(x)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>[7\ln(x) +5]'\amp = [7\ln(x)]' + [5]' </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp =  7[\ln(x)]' + 0 </mrow> 
            <mrow> \amp = 7\cdot \frac{1}{x} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \frac{7}{x}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x) = 3x^8 + 2e^x - 4\ln(x)</m>.  Find <m>f'(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow> [3x^8 + 2e^x - 4\ln(x)] \amp = [3x^8]' + [2e^x]' - [4\ln(x)]' </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp  = 3[x^8]' + 2[e^x]' - 4[\ln(x)]'</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = 3\cdot 8x^7 + 2e^x - 4\cdot \frac{1}{x}</mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = 24 x^7 + 2e^x - \frac{4}{x}</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x) = e^x + x^e </m>.  Find <m>f'(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This problem requires <em>very careful reading</em>.  
          The key is to remember that our <em>only variable is <m>\red x</m></em>.  The other characters <m>e</m> and <m>2</m> both refer to constant numbers.
          This is where <m>\frac{d}{dx}</m> notation shines, since it reminds us that the vairable is <m>\red x</m>. 
          <md>
            <mrow> f'(x) \amp = \ddx{ e^{\red x} + {\red x}^e} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \ddx{e^{\red x}} + \ddx{{\red x}^e}  </mrow>
          </md>
          Look very carefully about where the variable is in each term.  In the first term, <m>x</m> is in the exponent, so use the exponential rule
          <me>
            \ddx{e^{\red x}} = e^{\red x}
          </me>
          In the second term, <m>x</m> is in the base, so use the power rule with <m>\blue m = \blue e = \blue 2.718\dots</m>
          <me>
            \ddx{{\red x}^{\blue m} = \blue m {\red x}^{\blue m - 1}}
          </me>
          Putting this all together  gives the following
          <md>
            <mrow> f'(x) \amp = \ddx{ e^{\red x} + {\red x}^e} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \ddx{e^{\red x}} + \ddx{{\red x}^e}  </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = e^{\red x} + {\blue e}{\red x}^{\blue e-1}  </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
    <task>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f(x) = e^2 + 2^e</m>.  Find <m>f'(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This problem requires <em>very careful reading</em>.  
          The key is to remember that our <em>only variable is <m>\red x</m></em>.  The other characters <m>e</m> and <m>2</m> both refer to constant numbers.
          This is where <m>\frac{d}{dx}</m> notation shines, since it reminds us that the vairable is <m>\red x</m>. 
          <md>
            <mrow> f'(x) \amp = \ddx{  e^2 + 2^e} </mrow>
          </md>
          Note that there are no <m>\red x</m>'s in either term.  That means we can type them into our calculator and replace them with numbers: <m>e^2 = 7.389\dots</m> and <m>2^e = 6.580\dots</m>.  Putting this in and using our derivative rules gives the following
          <md>
            <mrow> f'(x) \amp = \ddx{  7.389 + 6.580} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = \ddx{7.389} + \ddx{6.580} </mrow>
            <mrow> \amp = 0 + 0 </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </task>
  </exploration>

